#: ../../Chemistry_of_Water_Treatment/Chemistry_Derivations.rst:88
msgid "Acid Neutralizing Capacity (ANC) or Alkalinity"
msgstr ""

#: ../../Chemistry_of_Water_Treatment/Chemistry_Derivations.rst:90
msgid ""
"Acid neutralizing capacity or alkalinity is the ability of a water sample"
" to react with and neutralize an input of acid. The units of ANC are "
"equivalents (or protons) per liter. Bicarbonate, :math:`HCO_3^-`, can "
"react with one proton, :math:`H^+`, and thus each mole of :math:`HCO_3^-`"
" provides one equivalent per liter of ANC. The other terms in the "
"equation have similar explanations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../Chemistry_of_Water_Treatment/Chemistry_Derivations.rst:94
msgid ""
"Note that carbonic acid and dissolved carbon dioxide are not in the ANC "
"equation because they have no ability to neutralize protons."
msgstr ""

